## Step 5 — Initialize the repository and commit

```
cd %USERPROFILE%\Desktop\fc0u71-tech-plus-practice-exam
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: FC0-U71 full practice exam, README, SETUP"
```

You should see output ending with something like:
```
[main (root-commit) abc1234] Initial commit: FC0-U71 full practice exam, README, SETUP
 3 files changed, ...
```

---

## Step 6 — Connect to GitHub and push

```
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/DrMarioDeSean411-arch/fc0u71-tech-plus-practice-exam.git
git push -u origin main
```

Git will ask for your GitHub credentials:
- **Username:** `DrMarioDeSean411-arch`
- **Password:** use a **Personal Access Token**, NOT your GitHub account password

**To create a Personal Access Token (PAT):**
1. Go to https://github.com/settings/tokens
2. Click **Generate new token (classic)**
3. Name it `fc0u71-deploy`
4. Set expiration to 90 days
5. Check the **repo** scope (top checkbox under scopes)
6. Click **Generate token** at the bottom
7. **Copy the token immediately** — you cannot see it again after leaving the page

Paste the token when Command Prompt asks for your password. The characters will not appear on screen — that is normal. Press Enter.

If you already have a saved PAT from a prior repo (e.g., d335-python-practice-exam) and it has not expired, Windows Credential Manager may reuse it automatically and skip this prompt entirely.

---

## Step 7 — Enable GitHub Pages

1. Go to https://github.com/DrMarioDeSean411-arch/fc0u71-tech-plus-practice-exam
2. Click **Settings** in the top navigation bar
3. Click **Pages** in the left sidebar (under "Code and automation")
4. Under **Source**, select **Deploy from a branch**
5. Under **Branch**, set it to `main` and folder `/` (root)
6. Click **Save**

Wait 2–3 minutes, then refresh the Settings → Pages screen. You will see:

```
Your site is live at https://DrMarioDeSean411-arch.github.io/fc0u71-tech-plus-practice-exam/
```

